"Noerdlinger P.D., Brower K.R.","The melting of floating ice raises the ocean level",2007,"Geophysical Journal International","170","1",,"145","150",,,10.1111/j.1365-246X.2007.03472.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34447279698&partnerID=40&md5=99af3bd6e1c7386a7f2e03937bfb7eb2","St. Mary's University, Department of Astronomy and Physics, Halifax, NS B3H 3C3, Canada; New Mexico Institute of Technology, Department of Chemistry, Socorro, NM 87801, United States; 1222 Oakleaf Circle, Boulder, CO 80304-1151, United States","Noerdlinger, P.D., St. Mary's University, Department of Astronomy and Physics, Halifax, NS B3H 3C3, Canada, 1222 Oakleaf Circle, Boulder, CO 80304-1151, United States; Brower, K.R., New Mexico Institute of Technology, Department of Chemistry, Socorro, NM 87801, United States","It is shown that the melting of ice floating on the ocean will introduce a volume of water about 2.6 per cent greater than that of the originally displaced sea water. The melting of floating ice in a global warming will cause the ocean to rise. If all the extant sea ice and floating shelf ice melted, the global sea level would rise about 4cm. The sliding of grounded ice into the sea, however, produces a mean water level rise in two parts; some of the rise is delayed. The first part, while the ice floats, is equal to the volume of displaced sea water. The second part, equal to 2.6 per cent of the first, is contributed as it melts. These effects result from the difference in volume of equal weights of fresh and salt water. This component of sea rise is apparently unrecognized in the literature to date, although it can be interpreted as a form of halosteric sea level change by regarding the displaced salt water and the meltwater (even before melting) as a unit. Although salinity changes are known to affect sea level, all existing analyses omit our calculated volume change. We present a protocol that can be used to calculate global sea level rise on the basis of the addition of meltwater from grounded and floating ice; of course thermosteric volume change must be added. © 2007 The Authors Journal compilation © 2007 RAS.","Density; Laboratory measurement; Oceans; Present-dayice melting; Sea level change","floating ice; laboratory method; meltwater; salinity; sea level change; seawater; water level",,,,,,"Alley, R.B., Clark, P.U., Huybrechts, P., Joughin, I., Ice-sheet and sea level changes (2005) Science, 310, pp. 456-460; Antonov, J.I., Levitus, S., Boyer, T.P., Steric sea level variations during 1957-1994: Importance of salinity (2002) J. Geophys Res., 107 (C12), p. 8013. , doi 10.1029/2001JC000964; On Floating Bodies, , Archimedes, ca. 220BC. 2 volumes doi 10.1029/2001JC000964; Bamber, J., Vaughan, D., Joughin, I., Widespread complex flow in the Interior of the Antarctic Ice Sheet (2000) Science, 287, pp. 1248-1250; Bindschadler, R., Hitting the ice sheets where it hurts (2006) Science, 311, pp. 1720-1721; Blankenship, D., Peters, M., Young, D., Morse, D., Detection of a thick water sheet beneath an ice stream tributary in West Antarctica (2006) Geophys. Res. Abstracts, 8. , 09875 SRef-ID: 1607-7962/gra/EGU06-A-09875; Braun, C., Hardy, D., Bradley, R., Surface mass balance of the ward hunt ice rise and ward hunt ice shelf, Nunavut, Canada (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109. , D22110, doi 10.1029/2004JD004560; Antarctic factsheet -geographical statistics (2005), http://www.antarctica.ac.uk/Resources/schoolzone/resources/Factsheets/ factsheet_geostats_screen.pdf, British Antarctic Survey, Natural Environment Research Council doi 10.1029/2004JD004560Cavalieri, D.J., Parkinson, C.L., Vinnikov, K., 30-Year satellite record reveals contrasting Arctic and Antarctic sea ice variability (2003) Geophys. Res. Lett., 30, p. 1970. , doi 10.1029/2003GL018031; Cazenave, A., Nerem, R.S., Present-day sea level change: Observations and causes (2004) Rev. Geophys., 42. , RG3001, doi 10.1029/2003RG000139; Church, J.A., Gregory, J.M., Huybrechts, P